ermediate or symbolic results—report only the final $T_f$ in $\\mathrm{K}$.\\n\\nAssumptions:\\n\\n\\begin{itemize}\\n  \\item The \"doubling\" of the field (factor 2) sets the quench surface field: quench occurs when $2\\gamma B_x(z)$ first equals $B_c(T_i)$; for EMF and heating, use laboratory $B_x(z)$.\\n  \\item The EMF driving Ohmic heating arises solely from the rod's motion through the transverse $\\vec{B}(z)$, with direction such that it induces an azimuthal current around $y$ (ignore any external circuit).\\n  \\item The Ohmic heating is calculated in the laboratory frame and all energy appears as increased proper thermal energy in the rod (ignore relativistic corrections to heat addition).\\n  \\item Field variations across the finite diameter and demagnetising/magnetisation energy terms are neglected.\\n  \\item All parameters not explicitly specified may be ignored.\\n\\end{itemize}\\n\\nWhat is the final uniform proper temperature $T_f$ (in $\\mathrm{K}$) of the rod when its center reaches $z_f = 5.000\\,\\mathrm{m}$?",
